<BlogLayout
  title="What I Learned at the Rolex Fastnet Race"
  description="Racing from Cowes to Cherbourg via the Fastnet Rock. What breaks on boats, what holds, and how offshore racing shapes how I think about fabrication."
  datePublished="2025-10-20"
  author="Ken"
>
  <h2>The Fastnet</h2>

  <p>
    The Rolex Fastnet Race is one of offshore sailing's marquee events. Start in Cowes on the Isle of Wight, sail west down the English Channel, round Fastnet Rock off the southwest coast of Ireland, and finish in Cherbourg, France. Roughly 695 nautical miles of some of the most challenging waters in the world.
  </p>

  <p>
    I was there as crew, not as a tourist. The experience was brutal and brilliant in equal measure, and it completely reinforced why 3D3D focuses on marine fabrication the way we do.
  </p>

  <h2>What Breaks</h2>

  <p>
    Offshore racing destroys equipment. Not slowly, but violently. The loads on a racing yacht are enormous. Sails generate thousands of pounds of force. Rigging is under constant tension. Hardware is at the limit of its design envelope, and the sea doesn't care about your design envelope.
  </p>

  <p>
    During the race, I watched the following happen across our boat and the fleet:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Fairlead bases cracking from repeated shock loading.</li>
    <li>Instrument housings splitting where the mounting screws created stress risers.</li>
    <li>Sail track cars jamming because the plastic guide inserts wore through.</li>
    <li>A nav station bracket ripping out of its mounting point. The screws held, the plastic didn't.</li>
    <li>A water strainer housing cracking from vibration fatigue.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Every single one of those failures was a plastic part. Not a metal part, a plastic part. And every single one of them could have been printed better, in a better material, with better geometry.
  </p>

  <h2>What Holds</h2>

  <p>
    The parts that survived were the ones designed with respect for the environment. Stainless steel hardware, properly engineered composite components, and on one boat I talked to, 3D printed parts in ASA and PETG-CF that the skipper had made specifically for racing loads.
  </p>

  <p>
    That skipper got it. He'd printed replacement fairlead inserts with carbon-fiber-filled PETG, oriented the layers along the load path, and used enough wall thickness to handle the shock. They held the entire race while the factory originals on other boats were cracking.
  </p>

  <p>
    The lesson is simple: material selection and print orientation aren't optional decisions. They're the decisions that determine whether your part survives or ends up as debris in the bilge.
  </p>

  <h2>Conditions Test Everything</h2>

  <p>
    The Fastnet showed me conditions I hadn't experienced before. The Celtic Sea doesn't behave like the Atlantic off Nova Scotia. The wave patterns are sharper, more confused. The current in the Irish Sea adds another layer of chaos. Cold spray, constant heel, and 30+ hours without proper sleep.
  </p>

  <p>
    In those conditions, you learn what matters. Complicated mechanisms fail. Simple, robust designs survive. Parts with generous radii instead of sharp corners last. Parts with solid walls instead of fancy lattice infill hold together.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <p>Simplicity is the ultimate sophistication, and that applies to printed parts as much as it applies to sailing.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>How It Changed 3D3D</h2>

  <p>
    After the Fastnet, I redesigned several of our standard marine parts. Increased wall thicknesses. Eliminated sharp internal corners. Changed default infill from 20% grid to 40% cubic. Moved from PETG to ASA as the default outdoor marine material.
  </p>

  <p>
    I also started thinking more seriously about onboard printing, which led directly to our Newport Bermuda Race campaign. If parts are breaking offshore and can be identified, modeled, and printed while underway, the whole equation of offshore self-sufficiency changes.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Fastnet was a masterclass in failure analysis, delivered by the Atlantic Ocean at full volume. I took notes. The parts we make now are better because of it.
  </p>
